 Royale & Wande) - Single by 116|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/live-forever-feat-1k-phew-aaron-cole-hulvey-tedashii/1494970620|language=en-us|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n|Non-album single\n|-\n|\"We Fight (Color Purple)\" ([[Datin (rapper)|Datin]] featuring 1K Phew and Wande)\n|March 13, 2020<ref>{{Citation|title=We Fight (Color Purple) [feat. 1K Phew & Wande] - Single by Datin|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/we-fight-color-purple-feat-1k-phew-wande-single/1499169870|language=en-us|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n|Non-album single\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Rappers from Austin]]\n[[Category:Nigerian female rappers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American female rappers]]\n[[Category:Reach Records artists]]\n[[Category:A&R people]]\n[[Category:American people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin alumni]]\n[[Category:1990s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:Alpha Kappa Alpha]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Round Rock]]\n[[Category:Sigma Phi Lambda]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| background       = solo_singer\n| name             = Wande\n| birth_name       = Yewande Isola\n| birth_date       = {{birth based on age as of date |24|2019|04|12}}\n| birth_place      = [[Nigeria]]\n| origin           = [[Austin, Texas]]\n| image            = \n| genre            = [[Christian hip hop]]\n| occupation       = Rapper, A&R administrator\n| label            = [[Reach Records|Reach]], Anike Sounds, OMGitsWande\n| associated_acts  = [[116 (hip hop group)|116]]\n| website          = {{url|omgitswande.com/}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| alias            = Wande Isola\n}}\n\n'''Yewande Isola''', professionally known as '''Wande''', is a [[Nigerian Americans|Nigerian American]] [[Christian hip hop]] artist and [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] administrator from [[Austin, Texas]]. She signed to the Christian hip hop label [[Reach Records]] in 2019, where she had worked as an A&R administrator. Prior to that, as an independent artist, from 2013 through 2018 she released multiple singles and made numerous featured appearances on various songs. She is the first woman signed to Reach.\n\n== Biography ==\n\nWande was born in Nigeria and raised in [[Round Rock, Texas|Round Rock]] and then Austin, Texas.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://godreports.com/2019/04/rising-rapper-overcame-muslim-family-opposition-to-follow-jesus/|title=Rising rapper overcame Muslim family opposition to follow Jesus|last=Ashcraft|first=Michael|date=April 12, 2019|website=God Reports|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> In addition to English, she is fluent in [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.onetribemag.com/2019/03/27/women-to-watch-rapper-wande-isola/|title=Women to Watch: Rapper, Wande Isola|last=Ebe|date=2019-03-27|website=OneTribeMag|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Most of her family was [[Muslims|Muslim]], except for her mother, who was Christian.<ref name=\":6\" /> She converted to Christianity in seventh grade while attending a camp in 2009 in [[Columbus, Texas]], a decision for which she encountered opposition from within her family.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2019/08/15/christian-rappers-you-need-know-including-chart-topper-nf/1987932001/|title=Christian hip hop is having a moment: 6 rappers you should know, including chart-topper NF|last=Ryan|first=Patrick|date=August 15, 2019|website=[[USA Today]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nShe became interested in [[rapping]] after a biology teacher allowed her to compose a rap about [[Membrane transport protein|cellular transport]] instead of writing an essay or making a presentation.<ref name=\":0\" /> She majored in journalism and public relations at [[University of Texas at Austin]], and rapped at campus events as a form of [[Christian ministry]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> She was a member of the [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] and [[Sigma Phi Lambda]] sororities, the [[National Association of Black Journalists]], IGotSole Dance Company, and the Texas Orange Jackets.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hercampus.com/school/texas/look-out-wande-isola|title=Look Out for Wande Isola|last=Rollins|first=Kara|date=November 16, 2015|website=[[Her Campus]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://moody.utexas.edu/news/outstanding-spring-2018-grads|title=Outstanding Spring 2018 Grads|last=Anonymous|first=|date=May 2, 2018|website=Moody College of Communication|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Her first released record was a feature on the song \"B.I.G.\" by D-Flow on their 2013 album ''Quarter to Vinci''.<ref name=\":2\" /> She released her first single, \"No Flex\" featuring ikilledmarlon, in May 2016.<ref name=\":3\" /> She performed at [[South by Southwest]] in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2016/03/10/sxsw-2016-music-lineup-heres-the-complete-list/|title=SXSW 2016 music lineup: Here\u2019s the complete list|last=Harrington|first=Jim|date=2016-03-10|website=[[The Mercury News]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/music/2017-01-19/sxsw-music-list-four/|title=SXSW Music List Four|last=Curtin|first=Kevin|date=January 19, 2017|website=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qromag.com/features/sxsw-2017-preview-friday/|title=SXSW 2017 Preview \u2013 Friday|last=|first=|date=March 11, 2017|website=QRO Magazine|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> and 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qromag.com/features/sxsw-2018-preview-friday/|title=SXSW 2018 Preview \u2013 Friday|last=|first=|date=March 4, 2018|website=QRO Magazine|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In 2017, while still pursuing her university education, she began an internship at Reach Records, and shortly before her graduation in 2018 she was hired as an administrator for the label's A&R.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxan.com/news/local/austin/blessed-up-ut-austin-alumna-wande-isola-signs-with-record-label/|title=\u2018Blessed Up\u2019: UT Austin alumna Wande Isola signs with record label|last=Moreno|first=Chelsea|date=2019-05-01|website=[[KXAN-TV]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The following year she was signed as a recording artist to the label,<ref name=\":4\" /> and she released her debut single on the label, \"Blessed Up\", in April.<ref name=\":5\">{{Citation|title=Blessed Up - Single by Wande|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/blessed-up-single/1459386367|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nWande is the first woman signed to the label.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/lecrae-signs-first-ever-female-artist-to-reach-records-wande.html|title=Lecrae signs first-ever female artist to Reach Records: Wande|last=Law|first=Jeannie|date=April 12, 2019|website=[[Christian Post]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> She has expressed a hope that her signing will make it easier for other women rappers to pursue a career in the highly male-dominated Christian hip hop genre. \"I think it\u2019ll show other labels that you shouldn\u2019t be afraid to sign females. I hear a lot of excuses like, 'Oh it\u2019s expensive' or 'Oh, we don\u2019t know how the market will react to a woman.' 'Will they buy her music?' Obviously, a lot of Christian companies don\u2019t have the money to just casually experiment with a Christian artist because you have to make sure they are profitable. So a lot of women get the short end of the stick because they don\u2019t want to gamble on a woman.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rapzilla.com/2019-04-wande-talks-about-signing-to-reach-records-whats-coming-next/|title=Wande Talks About Signing to Reach Records & What's Coming Next|last=Sarachik|first=Justin|date=2019-04-12|website=Rapzilla|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Singles ===\n\n==== As primary artist ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Title\n!Released\n!Album\n|-\n|\"No Flex\" (featuring ikilledmarlon)\n|May 27, 2016<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://rapzilla.com/2016-05-free-download-wande-no-flex-ft-ikilledmarlon/|title=Free Download: Wande - No Flex ft. ikilledmarlon|last=Solis|first=Steven|date=2016-05-27|website=Rapzilla|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n|Non-album single\n|-\n|\"They Didn't Know\"\n|July 14, 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rapzilla.com/2016-07-wande-they-didnt-know/|title=Free Download: Wande - They Didn't Know|last=Solis|first=Steven|date=2016-07-14|website=Rapzilla|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n|Non-album single\n|-\n|\"Hiatus Freestyle\"\n|December 5, 2017<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Hiatus Freestyle - Single by Wande|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/hiatus-freestyle-single/1322792319|volume=|pages=|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n|Non-album single\n|-\n|\"Elevated\" (featuring Bryon Juane)\n|April 19, 2018<ref>{{Citation|title=Elevated (feat. Byron Juane) - Single by Wande & PoetiCS|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/elevated-feat-byron-juane-s